    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so is that lactic acid buildup the only thing causing it? i've heard people talk about hydrogen ions too. how do those play into the actual stinging sensation specifically?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In addition to lactic acid, hydrogen ions (also known as protons) also contribute to the burning sensation during sprints. As lactic acid is formed, it releases hydrogen ions, which are acidic in nature and can directly stimulate nerve endings, causing pain. This is often referred to as the \"alarm\" response, where the high pH of the acidic lactic acid and hydrogen ions activates pain receptors, amplifying the sensation of burning.",
      "source": "target",
